Single Cell RNA-seq Analysis - differentiating between cell clusters

Jessica Zhang

2022-11-03

scRNA-seq Basics

Single cell RNA-sequencing is a an omic tool that enables the analysis of transcriptomic information from individual cells.

Here is a heavily simplifed step-by-step guide:

1. Prepare sample and sequence

  • Isolate cells from tissue of interest. In this case we are looking at mouse hindlimb skeletal muscle tissues 14 days post-injury
  • Each cell is barcoded with a specific oligo, so that all RNA sequences coming from the cell has the barcode sequence as a tail attached to it

2. Align all the reads to a reference genome using CellRanger.

3. Do a quality check of the RNA-seq and clean up the data using Seurat

  • nFeature_RNA - the number of different RNA sequences detected in each cell
  • nCount_RNA - the total number of RNA molecules detected in each cell
  • Filter data: only include data that falls within the normal range of nFeature_RNA (make sure the cells are alive) and nCount_RNA (make sure only a single cell is sequenced)

4. Perform some complex transformations to the data…

  • scRNA-seq data is multi-dimensional - think of the expression level of each individual gene as an axis.
  • Perform “dimensionality reduction” to visualise the data in a 2D plot
    PCA (principle component analysis) -> UMAP -> Feature plot

5. Identify each cell cluster’s identity using known markers

  • Use known databases and literatures
